://home.attbi.com/~bdemong/valaface.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Quid Pro Quo</span><hr size=1> The other day, it occurred to me that I know very little about the other realms' classes.  I mean, I know what a 'caster' is and what a 'tank' is, but for indentification specifics like what races they tend to be and what armor/weapons they tend to use, and combat specifics like what their distinct abilities are and how good they are at a particular function, I am slightly above clueless.  On the other hand, I could go into meticulous detail about every Hibernian class.  But enough about that...<br>
<br>
Did you know that during wartime, it is very common for enemy spies to secretly work together and share information?  For one thing, they probably have more in common with their counterparts than their superiors, and a similar objective perspective of politics and war.  For another, working together saves them a lot of work getting information they'd eventually find anyway, and as long as the reports keep coming, both sides' superiors are happy.  I find that supremely interesting, thought you might too. <p><img src="http://home.attbi.com/~bdemong/valarauco.gif"></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uvalarauco.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Valarauco</A> at: 2/7/02 12:30:22 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/ugrinkle.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Grinkle</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Safehouse Supporter</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/1/02 5:23:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousefrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2004.topic&index=1>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> <BR><img src=http://sigstuff1.homestead.com/files/Lute_pic.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Quid Pro Quo</span><hr size=1> Put 12 or so hours played into another char, and you'll know a fair amount about it, probably enough to ask some specific questions that are more likely to be answered than a general request for &quot;the lowdown&quot;. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/ulisboa.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lisboa</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/1/02 6:25:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousefrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2004.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> not the same</span><hr size=1> What he wants to know is what pieces of armor are particular characters wearing and what weapons they are using at his level.  This gives him an idea of what he is encountering when he meets up with say, a blue healer wielding a red two handed hammer.... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/ukeryath.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Keryath</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.twitchmonkey.com/~damnskippy/DAoC/kerface.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/4/02 12:31:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousefrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2004.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.twitchmonkey.com/~damnskippy/DAoC/kerface.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: not the same</span><hr size=1> Albions:<br>
<br>
<b>Plate</b>: you know it, you love it, and you want more of it.<br>
<br>
Plate is Paladin/Armsman. Nearly everyone 40+ is in black, that's all the good stuff. <br>
Best weapons right now are blue tinted. This may change with the Lyon itemization patch, that's the main grind zone right now so there will be a fast influx of new gear.<br>
<br>
<i>Armsmen</i> are usually with a polearm (easy to spot) or sword and shield. Tactics are very simple; they hit you with weapon of choice until you die. They also have crossbows and every now and then you'll run into one that put some points into it. Fear these people, they hit bloody hard with that toy.<br>
<br>
<i>Paladins</i> look much like Armsmen do, with the exception that many of them have a fondness for two-handed weapons (swords/axes pretty much exclusively. A few hammer, but that's about it). The rest follow the sword/shield path. They have few hp than Armsmen, but they have some nasty chants. You'll see golden spell effects above them.<br>
<i>Cup</i>: Heal chant, it's a tick based that does a group heal for about a normal hit at their level. Combat only.<br>
<i>Sword</i>: Group Damage adds.<br>
<i>Breastplate</i>: Group AF buff.<br>
A somewhat popular trick is to 'twist' these chants, causing the icons to switch rapidly. This will allows them to stack heal and damage add chants leaving you to face both. However, when you see this it also means they are rapidly draining their stamina and won't be able to sprint for long.<br>
The other ability to beware of is that most over 30 will be able to ress, and will have spare mana to do it.<br>
<br>
<b>Chain</b>:<br>
<br>
Black and red for the 40+, blue weapons right now.<br>
<br>
<i>Clerics</i> are almost always Hammer + Shield (Kite, medium). If they have another mace/hammer on their back, it's a cleric. Enhance spec clerics are weak in RvR; they mainly just buff the melees and try not to die. Rejuv clerics are a one trick heal pony, with two pretty amazing instant heal shouts. Smite clerics are the devil. In an RvR environment, you'll mainly see smite clerics. Most RvR clerics, even those of a different prime spec, will invest in smite.<br>
They'll have a self-damage add, at least 1 insta shout heal.<br>
They'll have a point blank AE shout damage spell; this is troublesome but not overly deadly in itself. However, it takes very little mana so many clerics that are standing around will pop it off as an  'assassin check'.<br>
They also have an instant shout point blank AE mez, this is a killer. The higher those clerics specs in smite, the longer the duration on the mez. A full spec smite cleric can do 40+ seconds or so on it. Low spec can do perhaps 10.<br>
They also have a single target stun that doesn't last long at all and has crappy range, and a medium range nuke that does 'good' damage.<br>
Clerics can't quickcast, so if you melee them you only have to worry about the 2 instant cast heals, the instant cast PB AE DD, and the instant cast PB AE Mez.<br>
Fun huh?<br>
<br>
<i>Minstrels</i>? If you see a chain class with a shield (small, round) + sword/rapier and some nice bright green glowing stuff.. it's a minstrel. Like bards, they're forced to have an instrument equipped to do any of the song abilities.<br>
<i>Lute</i> - Heal song. It sucks, rarely used. Most minstrels don't carry one anymore.<br>
<i>Drums</i> - Speedy feets/power regen.<br>
<i>Flute</i> - Mez/Charm. Fear the flute.<br>
Instants:<br>
While they have three total shouts, last I checked 2 shared the same timer. The range is very short so it's pretty much a melee thing. This is good for them, due to the fact most of them melee as well as a slightly damp dishtowel.<br>
<i>DDx1</i><br>
<i>DDx2</i> (or <i>Stun</i>)<br>
Unlike the rest of the singing dancing classes, minstrels get stealth. This can ruin your day. However, much like the infiltrator, if you breathe on them funny they fall over dead. Prior to the mez/stun nerf they were feared with their ability to juggle stun/mez and kick the snot out of you with you unable to do anything but stand around watching.<br>
<br>
Last chain class is the <i>Mercenary</i>. Easy to spot these, they're the only chain class not using a shield. A weapon in both hands, once again sword is the norm. There are a few crush spec mercs that use maces/hammers but most of these give up and go to Midgard, heh. Nothing really amazing here, their short bow does crap damage so just ignore it, they do. They do output a good amount of melee damage, but their main benefit is that everyone ignores them in favor of the melees in plate that they can usually close with the weaker people on your side. Other than they dual wield they're pretty bland. Oh! And every 30 minutes they can make you fumble. Not that it'll happen since pretty much all of them are so irritated with the skill they refuse to hotkey it.<br>
<br>
<b>Studded</b>:<br>
<br>
He's got a bow. He's got stealth. He's a <i>Scout</i>. The weakest of the overpowered archers, they don't get pets, good melee, or speed shouts like the rest of the girls. They do get a bit better range but that's about it. If you want to kill archers, kill scouts. In melee they'll use a sword or thruster with a small shield. Most of them have horrid thrust skills since they quit training it after level 12 when they figure out how much they suck at it, so will attempt to run away anyhow. If you spot them and can close before he gets a crit off, they're meat.<br>
<br>
And like the rest of Albion, they're mostly in black.<br>
<br>
<b>Leather</b>:<br>
<br>
<i>Infiltrators</i> - Nightshades with a crossbow instead of the DD. Crappier non-Crit style overlaps. Lame. They wear black and purple at 40+<br>
<br>
<i>Friars</i> - Heh. Unlikely you'll see one. Easy to spot though, if you see anyone in a robe wearing a visible hat, it's a friar. Their best trick is to sit around pretending to be an int caster. Moderate melee, some heals. Their enhance spells are still bugged so no one trains in them. Weak. I'm not sure what they wear anymore, as I don't see them often.<br>
<br>
<b>Cloth</b>:<br>
They are usually in black with no hat. They have sticks. If it's a Saracen it's a mage type so no damage add, but high chance of mez. Avalonians have 40 base con so are easy targets.<br>
<br>
If you see a Highlander in a robe it's a melee trying to be funny.<br>
If you see anyone in a robe that has a visible hat, it's not a caster.<br>
<br>
If you see a big dopey overweight statue looking thing, you're seeing the only high-level cabalist on the server. Let him kill you so he'll feel better and keep playing. Someone has to be the butt of the jokes.<br>
<br>
If you see any other type of mob/pet following a caster, it's a sorcerer. They have lots of ranged mez but are rare as heck.<br>
<br>
The non-pets are wizards and thurgs. Wizards are lame; they have some DD and some more DD, and some Area DD. All their DDs do less than any of the other casters. Most have quit. Thurgs are pretty brutal, they'll have refreshing party bubble up pretty much at all times, as well as the minor run buff. They are a one-man zergling raid, so pop them before they start chaining pets. They'll have a nasty damage add and melee haste going, so watch out.<br>
<br>
So.. who's next? <p><center><img src=http://www.twitchmonkey.com/~damnskippy/DAoC/kerysmall2.jpg></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uvalarauco.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Valarauco</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/4/02 1:09:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousefrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2004.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~bdemong/valaface.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: not the same</span><hr size=1> I meant via email (everyone in DAoC is going to link to this thread now and I’ll be the reason it exists <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->              ), but since you sold out Albion, I’ll sell out Hibernia and hope someone posts Midgard.<br>
<br>
Hibernians<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>             Scale (easy to tell scale from other armor, it has… um, scales)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Druid: Usually Celt or Firbolg, small (round) shield and a blade or blunt weapon. High level scale armor is black or crimson, medium-high is teal, but of course people can enamel it. If they have a black wolf, a lynx, or a walking tree, it’s a Druid.  Primary healing class of Hibernia, they get all that insta-heal goodness, good buffs, AE root if they speced it, DOT poison if they speced it (stronger/longer than equivalent-level Envenom DOT), and can’t spec weaponskill but have high AF/Abs/HP. Rez.<br>
<br>
Warden: Usually Firbolg but sometimes Celt, with a medium (kite) shield and a blunt (mace or spiked club) weapon.  This description can also fit a Hero but if you see it cast, it’s a Warden. They can heal but most don’t spec very high in it, almost all Wardens spec at least high enough for the first version of group bladeturn chant (pulsing, every 10? seconds for low spec, 6 sec for high spec), and some spec pretty high in weaponskill (which will hurt you, a lot).  Decent buffs, high HP, good armor.  Can also make a party run fast but not as fast as a bard, and not while chanting bladeturn. Rez.<br>
<br>
Hero: Firbolg or Celt with a spear is a Hero, Firbolg or Celt with either a medium (kite) or large (tower) shield and a one-handed sword is probably a Hero, Fir/Celt with shield/mace is 50/50 chance for Hero/Warden, Fir/Celt with two-handed sword or branch-looking club or two-handed mace is 75/25 either Hero or (Celt only) Champion (reason for 75/25 is there are 3x as many Heroes as Champions).  Same as armsman, they hit you til you die.  They can also turn into a deer for +30-50% hit points for 30 seconds.  Spear or Large Weaponry (2-handed non-spear) heroes will hit you really hard (usually max spec in Celtic Spear or LW, and Parry), Shield Heros will hit you kinda hard but are basically turtles (very high Block and Parry spec) and may stun you with shield styles. <br>
<br>
Champion: Celt (every once in a blue moon you'll see a Lurikeen champion -- don't step on them or you'll lose a leg. I have never seen an Elven Champion), usually large weapon (2-handed sword, 2-handed mace, a club that looks like a treebranch, etc).  Similar to Blademaster but get some spells, notably debuff shouts that were just nerfed slightly harder than Enervating poison.  If you have low con or str this can still be dangerous.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>             Reinforced (anything that isn’t obviously wearing Scale or a robe, or is a Nightshade, is wearing Reinforced, though it can be hard to tell reinf just by sight)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Bard: Firbolg or Celt, musical instrument or little note particles is a giveaway, otherwise they use small (round) shields and usually a mace or club.  They can heal but don’t tend to spec very high in it, AE mez, single-target mez (can be very long duration, 51sec+), shout for wimpy damage, can spec in weapons and may have pretty decent skill in it, and like Druid and Warden have pretty good buffs, armor, and HP.  Oh yeah, they can run really fast. Same instrument-for-song as Minstrel above, but also Flute = Endurance Regen; melees in a party with a high-spec End-Bard can spam styles just shy of &quot;forever&quot;. Rez.<br>
<br>
Blademaster: Celt or Firbolg.  Two swords.  A third, floating, green-flaming sword for 50% more damage every 30 mins.  No spells. Tend to have very high weapon/dual/parry spec.<br>
<br>
Ranger: Lurikeen usually, Elf or Celt sometimes.  The two blades or daggers at their belt are just for show (well, not really, but I wouldn’t fear their melee like I fear Hunters).  They shoot you, they stealth, they self-buff, they have a run-fast shout.  Not in that order.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>             Leather (high level leather is purple and black, most shades dye black anyway)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Nightshade: Elf or Lurikeen. Just like you except usually dual-wield daggers (or a rapier and a dagger) and can cast an 80-ish damage nuke at high levels.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>             Cloth</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
All three casters use a robe (with hat) and a crystal-tipped staff that looks kind of like a spear at a glance. You can't tell the 3 classes apart until they start casting, unless it's an Enchanter with a pet up. All have a personal non-pulsing bladeturn.<br>
<br>
Enchanter: If you see a lurikeen or elf pet (underhill ally, for example) it’s an Enchanter.  They damage buff and nuke mostly, but can also make a party run fast (about the same as Warden).<br>
<br>
Eldritch: The nukers.  Either have AE damage (and nukes) or AE disease (and nukes), usually the former.  The area void bolt thingie is Eldritch, single-target void bolt is probably Eldritch because you're more likely to find the Easter Bunny than a high-level Mentalist.<br>
<br>
Mentalist: Rare. Depending on spec they will be good at two of the following three things: Healing, Nuking, Mez/Stun.  Usually Nuke and Mez/Stun as far as I can tell, but I haven’t met many. Their mez is single-target. I'm not sure if their DOT is baseline or Nuke spec.  Ditto for snare.<br>
 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uvalarauco.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Valarauco</A> at: 2/4/02 4:38:36 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/ukeryath.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Keryath</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.twitchmonkey.com/~damnskippy/DAoC/kerface.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/4/02 1:41:10 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousefrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2004.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.twitchmonkey.com/~damnskippy/DAoC/kerface.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: not the same</span><hr size=1> I know you meant via email, I just didn't care =P<br>
<br>
Anything to make the game a bit more interesting is good in my book. If people can identify the other players, perhaps we might find some <i>tactics</i>, instead of the 'everyone rush in and whack something'. Or the Midgard version: 'Lemme just AE stun 'em all, har har.'<br>
<br>
